    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bdaa14c3_2ede437a",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T00:08:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s a bit tricky to implement flaky tests this way.\nBecause @computed tracks all the @observables accessed during computation, which does not include variables referenced in callbacks.\nAnd because the yielded variants can be modified when new results are fetched, we need to apply the flakiness filter where those variants are accessed.\nIs it possible to implement that on ResultDB? Since ResultDB is already able to tell variants with unexpected result, I imagine it shouldn\u0027t be hard to implement a VariantWithOnlyUnexpectedResult filter?",
      "parentUuid": "a79cfd4d_83071f6a",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e77bb2b8_c9961c5f",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T06:51:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it is possible but then again, it would mean that merely checking/unchecking checkboxes would cause refetching data that ResultUI already has. It would be slow and unnecessary. \n\nI am also not sure ResultDB would be a good place for this because this problem is specific to ResultUI, so ideally it is solved by ResultUI. For example, we could implement any kind of filtering that you need in resultdb.js with caching. Then even though *this* file would look like a new request to resultdb.js is made, resultdb.js actually reuses the cached response and responds immediately.",
      "parentUuid": "bdaa14c3_2ede437a",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "aedcb27c_803c3130",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T07:14:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Are results included in different invocations guaranteed to have different variant tags?\nIf not, it\u0027s not possible to implement flaky filter in the frontend. Because we don\u0027t have all the data. An expected variant may become flaky if we receive an unexpected result in the next page.\nI can implement the flaky filter (in the frontend) in one of the following ways:\n1. implement it in iterator level. Then if a test results become flaky after a new test result page is fetched, it will still present on the page.\n2. implement in in the consumer level. Then if a test results become flaky after a new test result page is fetched, it will disappear from the page (which also means the page no longer always expand in one direction).",
      "parentUuid": "e77bb2b8_c9961c5f",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f98d4227_c433bef1",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1178685
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T07:16:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e If not, it\u0027s not possible to implement flaky filter in the frontend.\n\nIf not, it\u0027s not possible to implement flaky filter in resultdb.js.",
      "parentUuid": "aedcb27c_803c3130",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0ba587d0_e787236b",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/resultui/src/pages/invocation_page/context.ts",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-28T07:37:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "good point.\n\nI think (2) is fine here: although it is possible for the same test variant to be in different invocations, this is unlikely, so I expect to very rarely observe appearing/disappearing test variants. \n\nmore context: initally all test variants are sharded into smaller invocations (one test variant runs in one invocation) and those invocations are executed in parallel. In particular, we don\u0027t want to unnecessarily run the same test variant in different invocations because it would be duplication of work. \n\nIf a test is flaky, it is likely to have a mix of expected/unexpected results in the *same* invocation.\n\nNow suppose a test failed 3 times in a row. Currently Chromium recipe has a piece of code that hopes to still get a pass, so it retries the whole invocation. Then all test variants in that invocation are retried. and that previously failed test might pass. This is the case where failures might be in one inv, and pass may be in another, but then again, note that the test fail 3 times before that for this to happen. Note that if it does happen, then with 50% chance, we will see pass before failure because invocations are ordered by their hash in the database (so, random).\n\nfurther, currently rdb incorrectly marks OK results as unexpected, so we see a lot of redness/orangeness in ResultUI. Once that\u0027s fixed, the number of unexpected test results will shrink, so it is likely that all results will fit the first page (1000 results).\n\nAfter all, if it is still a problem, we can further reduce the probability of appearing/disappearing by increasing the page size.",
      "parentUuid": "f98d4227_c433bef1",
      "revId": "21fd86728de334a5a97d7cf9cb7a31f435381ad4",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    }
